 Debounce is a function that limits the execution rate of a function by delaying the actual execution after a certain amount of time has passed since the last execution. Here's a simple debounce function in JavaScript:

```javascript
function debounce(func, wait, immediate) {
  var timeout;
  return function() {
    var context = this,
        args = arguments;
    var later = function() {
      timeout = null;
      func.apply(context, args);
    };
    var callNow = immediate && !timeout;
    if (callNow) {
      func.apply(context, args);
    } else if (!immediate) {
      timeout = setTimeout(later, wait);
    }
    return {
      cancel: function() {
        clearTimeout(timeout);
      },
      call: function() {
        return func.apply(context, args);
      }
    };
  };
};
```

Example:

```javascript
// Define a function that updates the UI on every keystroke
function updateUI() {
  // Some code to update the UI
}

// Debounce the function to update the UI on every 500ms keystroke
var debouncedUpdateUI = debounce(updateUI, 500);

// Call the debounced function on every keystroke
document.addEventListener("keydown", debouncedUpdateUI);
```

Explanation: The `debounce` function takes three arguments: `func` is the function that needs to be debounced, `wait` is the time in milliseconds after which the function should be executed, and `immediate` determines whether the function should be executed immediately on the first call or only after the `wait` time has passed. The returned function has two additional methods: `cancel` can be used to cancel the execution of the debounced function, and `call` can be used to force the execution of the debounced function. In the example above, the `updateUI` function is debounced and bound to the `keydown` event of the `document`. This ensures that the UI is updated only after a certain amount of time has passed since the last keystroke.
